&lt;/div&gt;
</code></pre>

<h2>Controlling text size</h2>

<p>The base font size is 100% (16px default). Additionally:</p>

<h3>Font size multipliers</h3>

<p><code>t-xs</code>, <code>t-sm</code>, <code>t-md</code>, <code>t-lg</code>, <code>t-xl</code></p>

<p>Starting from your base font size, these multipliers will either increase or decrease the font size.</p>

<p><strong>Notes:</strong></p>

<ul>
  <li>The <code>t-md</code> class is the same as the base font size, and is set in REM. Use it to override other styles to return to the base font size.</li>
  <li>All other font size multipliers are set in EM, so that they will scale up or down depending on the parent element’s font size.</li>
  <li>Font size multipliers can be used on any element, but they are generally used on inline elements, e.g. <code>&lt;span&gt;</code>.
</ul>

<p>Example uses: smaller for footnotes or “small print”; larger for lead (intro) paragraphs.</p>

<table class="table">
  <thead>
    <tr>
      <th>Class</th>
      <th class="t-center">Font size multiplier</th>
      <th class="t-center">Pixel size (px) if base size is 16px</th>
      <th class="t-center">Example</th>
    </tr>
  </thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr>
      <td><code>t-xs</code></td>
      <td class="t-center">0.625em</td>
      <td class="t-center">10px</td>
      <td><span class="t-xs">Extra-small text</span></td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><code>t-sm</code></td>
      <td class="t-center">0.8125em</td>
      <td class="t-center">13px</td>
