<h3>Heading font-size utilities</h3>

<p><code>.h1</code>, <code>.h2</code>, <code>.h3</code>, <code>.h4</code>, <code>.h5</code>, <code>.h6</code></p>

<p>These are generally used on <em>block</em> (wrapper) elements, and they will resize text the same amount as for their respective heading tag sizes.</p>

<p>Example use: when you want to make text bigger (or large text smaller) without adversely affecting accessibility/ SEO heading hierarchy.</p>

<h3>Responsive font size multipliers</h3>

<p><code>t-long-read</code>, <code>t-comfort</code>, <code>t-display</code></p>

<p>These responsive font size multipliers can be used to make text even larger, but in a way that is not initially too large for phones and small tablet devices. These classes are applied to a wrapping element, and they will affect all text within that element. The font size will ramp up from 1× to a maximum value depending on the viewport width.</p>

<ol>
  <li>The <code>t-long-read</code> wrapping class ramps text up from 1× to 1.25× depending on viewport size.</li>
  <li>The <code>t-comfort</code> wrapping class ramps text up from 1× to 1.625× depending on viewport size.</li>
  <li>The <code>t-display</code> wrapping class ramps text up from 1× to 2× depending on viewport size.</li>
</ol>

